{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17511544","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17511544"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:43:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:43:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11755"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11755","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11755"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.51,0.37,0.06,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4368"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"33848"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4368","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4368"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11755"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"19123"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"8218"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6053"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8171"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42658"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"33848","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/33848"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 40-year-old man is being reviewed by his general practitioner for life insurance purposes. He is in good health and does not have any medical history of note. He does point out a swelling in his neck which he has had for several years and does not bother him unduly (image). On examination, his blood pressure is 115/82 mmHg, pulse 76/min and temperature 37.2\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. The swelling is smooth-surfaced and moves with swallowing. It does not move with tongue protrusion. His cervical lymph nodes are not palpable and the rest of the physical examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Review in one year","Thyroid function tests","Ultrasound neck","Ultrasound and fine needle aspiration","CT neck"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient has presented with an asymptomatic thyroid nodule. \u003Cstrong\u003EThyroid function tests \u003C/strong\u003Eare the initial investigation of choice for thyroid nodules that are found incidentally, where they can help in differentiating hyperthyroid from a hypothyroid or euthyroid gland, which will guide further investigations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReviewing in one year\u003C/strong\u003E would not be an ideal choice because with some thyroid cancers it is not possible to distinguish a benign thyroid nodule from a thyroid cancer clinically, even with the described history. Well-differentiated thyroid cancers (i.e. papillary or follicular thyroid cancer) may grow slowly, metastasise asymptomatically to the lung, and occur in a relatively young patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eultrasound neck \u003C/strong\u003Eis part of initial investigations for the evaluation of a thyroid nodule, but it would be usually done after the thyroid function tests, especially in the case of a hypothyroid or euthyroid gland to determine the Thyroid Imaging Reporting \u0026amp; Data System (TI-RADS) score and the subsequent risks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ethyroid ultrasound with FNAC\u003C/strong\u003E (fine needle aspiration cytology) would be most appropriate when there is a high suspicion of malignancy detected by the initial ultrasonography results.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA\u003Cstrong\u003E CT scan neck\u003C/strong\u003E would be the best option if a diagnosis of a malignant tumour of the thyroid gland had been established, where the scan was then used to assess the extent of the disease. It is also very helpful in assessing other pathologies of the neck area that are not visible using an ultrasound.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["A thyroid function test would be best initial investigation of choice for an asymptomatic, incidentally discovered thyroid nodule."],"references":["Bailey, Stuart, and Benjamin Wallwork. \u201cDifferentiating between benign and malignant thyroid nodules: An evidence-based approach in general practice.\u201d Australian journal of general practice vol. 47,11 (2018): 770-774. doi:10.31128/AJGP-03-18-4518","Venkatesh N, Ho JT. Investigating thyroid nodules. Aust Prescr 2021; 44:2004."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"19123"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11755"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19568"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19568","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19568"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/6de001fb-1768-4d19-8d5b-8caca5ba92eb.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/6de001fb-1768-4d19-8d5b-8caca5ba92eb.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"19123","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/19123"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-03-20T11:19:45+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-08T08:35:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4368"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"33848"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attribu